## SSR OP1 / OP2

### Marketing OP2

Primary focus shift due to Paid Search investment decrease from +11% YoY to -8% YoY related to delayed WW reimplementation of Google bidding, with growth driven by enhanced measurement and bidding functionality, and ungating access to AB via Guest experience.  

Paid Search (-8% investment YoY) growth is driven by reestablishing & improving Google Bidding, with bids informed by expected customer OPS, as well as improving conversion rate through Guest experience (pre-registration AB Shopping). 

We aim to bridge the gap between awareness and acquisition by creating deeper engagement and expanding the pool of ready-to-action prospects through Consideration campaigns. This approach leverages broad-scoping, intent-based campaigns to identify B2B targets, engaging prospects across their web journey through video and image-based ads. Since Paid Search (PS) targeting is limited to specific keywords entered by users, integrating Consideration campaigns allows us to increase PS bids toward warm prospects—those who have already engaged with Consideration ads. These prospects are pre-qualified through intent signals, such as visiting alternate B2B sites or engaging B2B content. We will measure success through surveyed prospects indicating AB purchase interest, increased ‘AB’ search volume among targeted users, and improved PS efficiency due to retargeting.

_OP2 Changes v OP1_
Paid Search Google Bidding: OP1 assumed reimplementation of Google Bidding WW Jan 1 2025. However, with an accelerated implementation we are now assuming Feb 1 WW (see Risks). Gap to OP1 is primarily driven by implementation timeline, however competitive headwinds have increased costs (Brand +43% CPC vs +25% expectation). While we expect Google Bidding and CX improvements (Guest) to help bridge the gap, we expect competition to continue impacting costs.

 Given reduction of paid search registrations specifically for SSR acquisitions, there is a need to build a more robust omnichannel strategy that looks beyond paid search to close the acquisition projected gap in 2025 and beyond.

Paid Search Google Bidding: For Paid Search we are assuming aggressive reimplementation of Google Bidding, based on an accelerated implementation path (Feb 1 launch WW). The accelerated path presents risk and new interpretations of product terms that require alignment across business, legal, and privacy leadership. However, the path enables WW support within 4 weeks (pending leadership alignment) vs Retail support for limited markets with extended setup (US in Q2, UK & DE Q3 only), enabling capture of +64k reg, +$33.4M 1-yr OPS vs solely leveraging Retail OCI only.

Paid Search Google Bidding: OP1 assumed reimplementation of Google Bidding WW Jan 1 2025. However, launch is now limited to US at end of Q2 and UK/DE at end of Q3. Implementation is reliant on Retail-created tech’s offline conversion import (OCI), which experienced delayed deployment by Retail due to technical and privacy challenges. As such, Retail has solely confirmed US, UK, and DE support within their 2025 roadmap, limiting ROW timeline scoping by AB. Tech is closely-aligned with Retail and will pivot to launch additional markets if Retail broadens regional support. In the interim, short-term proposed solutions are being evaluated (see Risks). Other options greatly reduce deployment requirements and support campaigns WW, but present business and legal risks which limits feasibility (Legal evaluation ETA EO Dec). Given reduction of paid search registrations specifically for SSR acquisitions, there is a need to build a more robust omnichannel strategy that looks beyond paid search to close the acquisition projected gap in 2025 and beyond.

